            "M3 Bolts 15 mm (5)",
            "M3 Bolts 30 mm (4)",
            "Magnets (2)",
            "Micro-motors, Wheel Kit & Bracket Kit",
            "Motor Brackets 3D Print File (optional spare)",
            "0.91\" OLED Screen",
            "L293D Motor Driver IC",
            "5 Channel IR Line Tracking Sensor",
            "Time of Flight Sensor (VL53L0X)",
            "CCA twin wire for connecting power bank to Arduino & Motors",
            "Screw Terminal Blocks"
        ],
        "description": "Wipy is an overly motivated whiteboard cleaner robot designed to automatically clean whiteboards. It uses magnets to stick to the board, wheels to move, a line-following sensor and sponge to erase, a time-of-flight sensor to measure distance, and an OLED screen to display a cute personality.",
        "steps": [
            "Prepare the base and case: Laser cut the base from acrylic or plywood and 3D print the case.",
            "Assemble the electronics: Connect the L293D Motor Driver to the mini-breadboard and Arduino extension shield. Attach jumper wires to the Arduino and motors. Load the sample code for the motors to test them.",
            "Assemble the base: Connect the motors to the top base using brackets and M2 nuts and bolts. Connect the Arduino to the top plate using M2 or M3 bolts. Attach bolts to the magnets, slide the bottom plate over the bolts, and attach the bolts to the middle plate. Attach the middle and bottom plates. Attach the line sensor to the middle plate. Add all bolts in the middle plate that connect to the top base. Finally, place and tighten the top base plate to the rest of the base.",
            "Adjust magnets: Experiment with magnet placement and spacers to achieve the right balance between adhesion and mobility on the whiteboard.",
            "Add sensors: Connect the line sensor, OLED screen, and Time of Flight sensor to the breadboard and Arduino.",
            "Upload code: Load the provided Arduino code, ensuring you have the necessary libraries installed.",
            "Provide power: Connect a power bank to supply power to both the Arduino and the motors.",
            "Final assembly: Tape the OLED and Time of Flight sensor to the case and attach the case to the base."
        ]
